\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 1. Project Overview\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Summary\b0\par
Grand Plaza Hotel is a five-star property located in Toronto, Ontario. The hotel previously managed all reservations manually using paper-based forms stored in filing cabinets. This system introduces a fully digital replacement covering the complete guest journey from initial inquiry through room selection, service add-ons, loyalty enrollment, payment, and checkout.\par
\par
The system is a JavaFX desktop application consisting of two primary interfaces: a self-service kiosk intended for use by arriving guests, and a password-protected administration portal for hotel staff. Both interfaces communicate with a shared MySQL database through a JPA-based data access layer.\par
\par

\b Key Features\b0\par
\tab - Self-service kiosk with a guided seven-step reservation workflow\par
\tab - Room selection with four categories and occupancy validation\par
\tab - Dynamic pricing using date-based strategy selection\par
\tab - Add-on service selection using the Decorator design pattern\par
\tab - Loyalty program enrollment and point tracking\par
\tab - Booking summary with CSV and PDF export\par
\tab - Admin dashboard with reservation search and reporting modules\par
\tab - Secure BCrypt password authentication for admin accounts\par
\tab - Rotating file-based audit logging with size limits\par
\tab - JPA persistence for all entities with Hibernate as the ORM provider\par
\par

\b Technologies Used\b0\par
\tab Language: Java 17\par
\tab UI: JavaFX 17 with FXML declarative layouts\par
\tab Database: MySQL 8\par
\tab ORM: Hibernate 5.6 with JPA 2.2 specification\par
\tab Security: jBCrypt 0.4 for password hashing\par
\tab Export: OpenCSV 5.8, OpenPDF 1.3\par
\tab Build: Apache Maven 3.8 via Maven Wrapper\par
\tab Runtime: GraalVM CE 25 (Java 17 compatible)\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 2. Architecture Summary\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Three-Tier Architecture\b0\par
The application strictly separates concerns across three tiers.\par
\par
The presentation tier consists of FXML layout files and their corresponding Java controller classes. Each screen in the kiosk and admin portal has its own FXML file and a dedicated controller. Controllers handle only UI events, validation messages, and scene transitions. No business logic resides in the controllers.\par
\par
The business logic tier contains service classes that enforce all business rules including pricing calculations, occupancy checks, loyalty point accumulation, and authentication. This tier also defines the design patterns that structure the system's core behaviour.\par
\par
The data tier consists of JPA entity classes mapped to MySQL tables, a singleton entity manager factory, and a utility class for database connection management. All database access goes through the EntityManager API.\par
\par

\b Cross-Cutting Concerns\b0\par
Logging is handled at every tier boundary. The LoggerUtil class configures a rotating file handler attached to the root logger. All significant actions including login attempts, reservation creation, errors, and database operations are captured in timestamped log entries.\par
\par
Exception handling uses a layered approach. Service methods throw checked exceptions when business rules are violated. Controllers catch these exceptions and display appropriate error messages to the user without exposing internal stack traces.\par
\par

\b MVC, DI, and ORM Usage\b0\par
The Model-View-Controller pattern is applied throughout. FXML files are the views. Controller classes are the controllers. Entity classes and service objects are the models. UIController passes itself as a dependency to sub-controllers using a setMainController method, providing a lightweight manual dependency injection mechanism without a framework.\par
\par
Hibernate ORM maps Java entity classes to relational tables. Annotations define column names, constraints, relationships, and cascade behaviour. JPQL queries in service classes retrieve filtered result sets from the database.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 3. Design Artifacts\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Class Diagram Overview\b0\par
The following describes the principal class relationships:\par
\par
\tab UIController holds BookingData (inner class, acts as session DTO)\par
\tab BookingData contains primitive fields for all booking state\par
\tab UIController implements PricingStrategy selection based on dates\par
\tab AddOnsController.BillComponent is implemented by BaseBill, WiFiDecorator, BreakfastDecorator, ShuttleDecorator, SpaDecorator\par
\tab Room is the abstract entity base. SingleRoom, DoubleRoom, PenthouseRoom extend it.\par
\tab RoomFactory instantiates concrete Room subclasses by type key\par
\tab Reservation has one Guest via foreign key and one list of Room objects\par
\tab Payment references a Reservation by foreign key\par
\tab Admin is an independent entity with username and BCrypt-hashed password\par
\tab JPAUtil is a static singleton managing EntityManagerFactory lifecycle\par
\tab AuthService uses JPAUtil to query and register Admin records\par
\tab BookingService uses JPAUtil to persist and retrieve Reservation records\par
\par

\b Sequence Diagram: Guest Reservation Flow\b0\par
\par
1. Guest launches application - Launcher initializes JPAUtil, registers admin, launches HotelApp\par
2. HotelApp loads welcome-view.fxml - UIController handles scene\par
3. Guest clicks Begin Reservation - UIController loads search-view.fxml with SearchController\par
4. Guest enters dates, guest count, and contact info - SearchController validates input\par
5. SearchController calls UIController.setSearchData() and triggers goToRoomSelection()\par
6. UIController loads room-selection-view.fxml with RoomSelectionController\par
7. Guest selects room type and quantity - RoomSelectionController validates occupancy\par
8. RoomSelectionController calls UIController.setRoomData() and triggers goToAddOns()\par
9. UIController loads addons-view.fxml with AddOnsController\par
10. Guest selects add-ons - AddOnsController builds decorated bill and previews total\par
11. AddOnsController calls UIController.setAddonsData() and triggers goToLoyalty()\par
12. UIController loads loyalty-view.fxml with LoyaltyController\par
13. Guest chooses enrollment - LoyaltyController calls UIController.setLoyaltyData()\par
14. UIController loads summary-view.fxml with SummaryController\par
15. SummaryController calls UIController.getTotal() and displays full breakdown\par
16. Guest clicks Confirm Booking - UIController calculates total and loads confirmation-view.fxml\par
17. ConfirmationController generates booking reference number\par
\par

