\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 4. Entity and Relationship Mapping\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Entities\b0\par
\par
Admin: Stores administrator credentials. Fields are id (auto-generated primary key), username (unique), password (BCrypt hash), and role.\par
\par
Guest: Represents a registered hotel guest. Fields are id, name, email, and phone. The phone number serves as the lookup key for loyalty status.\par
\par
Room: Abstract base entity mapped using InheritanceType.JOINED. Subclasses are SingleRoom, DoubleRoom, and PenthouseRoom. Fields are id, roomType (enum string), and pricePerNight.\par
\par
Reservation: Represents a booking. Fields are id, checkIn and checkOut dates, numberOfGuests, status, and a reference to the associated Guest. It also holds a list of Room objects.\par
\par
Payment: Represents a completed or pending payment. Fields are id, amount, paymentMethod, and paymentDate. It references a Reservation.\par
\par

\b Relationships and Annotations\b0\par
Guest to Reservation: One-to-many. A guest can have multiple reservations over time. The Reservation entity holds the foreign key.\par
\par
Reservation to Room: Many-to-many. A reservation can include multiple rooms. A room can be included in multiple reservations over different date ranges. This relationship is mapped using a join table.\par
\par
Payment to Reservation: One-to-one. Each payment record corresponds to exactly one reservation.\par
\par

\b Cascade and Fetch Notes\b0\par
Reservation cascades persist and merge operations to its associated Guest. Fetch type for Room lists is LAZY to avoid loading all room data on every reservation query. Payment uses EAGER fetch of its associated Reservation for billing display.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 5. Design Pattern Usage\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Singleton - JPAUtil\b0\par
The EntityManagerFactory is expensive to create and should exist only once per application lifecycle. JPAUtil uses a static field and a synchronized get method to ensure a single EntityManagerFactory is shared across all service classes. This is the classic thread-safe lazy singleton pattern.\par
\par

\b Factory - RoomFactory\b0\par
RoomFactory provides a static createRoom(String type) method that constructs and returns the appropriate Room subclass (SingleRoom, DoubleRoom, or PenthouseRoom) based on the type string. This isolates object creation from business logic and makes it easy to add new room categories without changing existing code.\par
\par

\b Strategy - Pricing\b0\par
Three pricing strategies implement the PricingStrategy interface: StandardPricing, WeekendPricing (multiplier 1.2), and PeakSeasonPricing (multiplier 1.3). UIController.getPricingStrategy() inspects the selected dates and returns the appropriate strategy at runtime. The strategy's calculatePrice() method is then called to determine the final room cost. This makes it trivial to add new pricing rules (e.g., holiday surcharges) without altering the pricing calculation entry point.\par
\par

\b Decorator - Add-on Billing\b0\par
The BillComponent interface defines getCost() and getDescription() methods. BaseBill holds the base room cost. Each add-on service (WiFiDecorator, BreakfastDecorator, ShuttleDecorator, SpaDecorator) wraps an existing BillComponent and adds the cost of one service on top. The decorators can be stacked in any order, producing a final bill that reflects all selected services. This eliminates conditional branching for pricing and makes adding a new service a matter of writing one new decorator class.\par
\par

\b Observer - Waitlist\b0\par
The Observer pattern is planned for the waitlist notification system. When a room type becomes available due to a cancellation, a RoomAvailabilityEvent is fired. All registered WaitlistObserver instances receive the notification and can display an alert to the waiting guest. This pattern decouples the availability check from the notification delivery mechanism.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 6. Business Rules\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Occupancy Limits\b0\par
Single Room: maximum 2 guests\par
Double Room: maximum 4 guests\par
Deluxe Room: maximum 2 guests\par
Penthouse Suite: maximum 2 guests\par
\par
Total capacity is calculated as the per-room maximum multiplied by the quantity selected. If the guest count entered on the search screen exceeds total capacity, the room selection screen blocks navigation and displays the exact difference.\par
\par

\b Pricing Rules\b0\par
Base rates per night:\par
\tab Single Room: 89 CAD\par
\tab Double Room: 129 CAD\par
\tab Deluxe Room: 199 CAD\par
\tab Penthouse Suite: 349 CAD\par
\par
Weekend surcharge: 20 percent markup applied when the majority of nights in the stay fall on a Saturday or Sunday.\par
Peak season surcharge: 30 percent markup applied when the stay overlaps with July, August, or December.\par
\par
Room base rate multiplied by the applicable strategy factor gives the per-night price. That value is multiplied by room quantity and number of nights.\par
\par

\b Add-on Pricing\b0\par
High-Speed WiFi: 9.99 per device per night\par
Daily Breakfast Package: 24.99 per person per night\par
Airport Shuttle: 35.00 per trip (flat fee)\par
Spa and Wellness: 49.99 per session (flat fee)\par
\par

\b Tax\b0\par
13 percent HST is applied to the combined room and add-on subtotal. This matches the Ontario provincial tax rate applicable to hotel accommodations.\par
\par

\b Loyalty Program Rules\b0\par
Enrollment is offered at the loyalty step during every booking. Guests earn 1 point for every 10 dollars spent on their stay. A balance of 100 points can be redeemed for a 10 dollar discount on a future booking. Upgrades and exclusive member rates are offered subject to availability.\par
\par

\b Cancellation Policy\b0\par
Cancellations must be made at least 24 hours before the scheduled check-in time. Late cancellations or no-shows are subject to a one-night penalty charge.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 7. Security and Logging\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Authentication\b0\par
Admin passwords are never stored in plain text. When a new admin is registered, the password is passed through BCrypt's hash function before being written to the database. During login, the plain-text entry is compared against the stored hash using BCrypt.checkpw(). The Admin entity holds only the hash.\par
\par
The initial admin account (username: nikan) is seeded by the Launcher on first run. If the account already exists, the duplicate entry exception is silently caught and ignored.\par
\par

\b Logging Configuration\b0\par
LoggerUtil configures a java.util.logging.FileHandler with:\par
\tab Log file pattern: system_logs.%g.log\par
\tab Maximum file size: 1 MB per file\par
\tab Maximum retained files: 10 (rotating)\par
\tab Formatter: SimpleFormatter with timestamp, level, and message\par
\par
Sample log entry format:\par
\tab Apr 07, 2026 12:34:51 AM com.seneca.hotelreservation_system.service.AuthService authenticate\par
\tab INFO: Admin login attempt for user: nikan - Result: SUCCESS\par
\par

\b Exception Handling Strategy\b0\par
Service methods declare checked exceptions for recoverable errors (invalid credentials, constraint violations, not-found entities). Controllers wrap service calls in try-catch blocks and display user-friendly Alert dialogs. Unrecoverable errors (database connection failure at startup) cause Launcher to print to System.err and exit before the UI is shown.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 8. Export and Reporting\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b CSV Export\b0\par
From the booking summary screen, guests can export their reservation details to a CSV file. The file is structured in labelled sections: Guest Information, Stay Details, Room Details, Add-ons, and Price Breakdown. Each field is written as a label-value pair on its own row. The file is saved to a user-selected location using a standard file chooser dialog.\par
\par

\b PDF Export\b0\par
The PDF export produces a plain-text receipt formatted with separators and column-aligned values. The header reads GRAND PLAZA HOTEL with the address and establishment year. Sections mirror the CSV structure. The footer thanks the guest and confirms that payment will be collected at the front desk.\par
\par
Both export formats use the OpenPDF and OpenCSV libraries included as Maven dependencies.\par
\par

\b Admin Reports\b0\par
The admin dashboard provides a reservation table that can be filtered by guest name, phone number, or reservation ID. Revenue and occupancy summary cards appear at the top of the dashboard. Extended reporting modules for billing, feedback, and waitlist management are accessible from the sidebar navigation.\par
\par\par

\pard\f0\fs32\b\ul 9. Challenges and Learnings\ulnone\b0\par
\fs20\par

\b Technical Challenges\b0\par
\par
The most significant architectural challenge was managing shared state across seven sequential kiosk screens without a framework. JavaFX does not natively support a shared session object between independently loaded FXML controllers. We resolved this by having UIController hold the BookingData inner class and passing itself to each sub-controller via a setMainController method. This was a deliberate compromise between simplicity and strict separation of concerns.\par
\par
ToggleGroup elements in FXML caused a runtime crash early in development. JavaFX attempts to add ToggleGroup as a Node child of its parent container, but ToggleGroup is not a Node. The solution is to declare it inside the parent element's resources block, then reference it from RadioButton elements using the dollar sign prefix syntax.\par
\par
Hibernate's schema generation on a fresh database required careful management of entity annotations. Missing cascade annotations caused detached entity exceptions during reservation persistence. Understanding which operations should cascade and which should not required iterative testing against a live MySQL instance.\par
\par

\b Individual Reflections\b0\par
\par
Working on this project taught the value of establishing a clear data flow early. We spent significant time late in development refactoring because early controller classes were too tightly coupled. A more deliberate upfront design of the BookingData session object would have saved considerable rework.\par
\par
The decorator pattern for add-on billing was initially unfamiliar but proved to be one of the most elegant solutions in the codebase. Once the base interface was established, each new add-on type took only minutes to implement without touching existing code.\par
\par
JavaFX's approach to scene management differs significantly from web-based frameworks. Loading a new FXML file replaces the entire scene graph, requiring that all stateful data be serialized to the session object before navigation. This constraint reinforced disciplined state management throughout the kiosk flow.\par
\par

\b Suggestions for Improvement\b0\par
\par
A dedicated session manager class would replace the current UIController-as-hub approach. Each controller would inject the session manager rather than receiving a reference to UIController, reducing coupling and improving testability.\par
\par
Unit tests for the service layer would have caught the pricing calculation bugs earlier. Adding JUnit 5 tests for PricingStrategy, the Decorator chain, and occupancy validation would increase confidence during refactoring.\par
\par
The current persistence layer uses Hibernate's built-in connection pool which is not intended for production. A connection pool such as HikariCP should replace it before any real deployment.\par
\par
The admin dashboard statistics (total reservations, rooms occupied, pending check-ins, waitlist) currently show placeholder values. Connecting these labels to live JPQL aggregate queries in BookingService would complete the reporting feature.\par
\par\par

